"Jungkunst H.F., Fiedler S.","Geomorphology - Key regulator of net methane and nitrous oxide fluxes from the pedosphere",2005,"Zeitschrift fur Geomorphologie","49","4",,"529","543",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-32144458051&partnerID=40&md5=87c47ce2d9aca6463c1d7d46ba338a8c","Max-Planck-Institute for Biogeochemistry, Hans-Knöll-Straße 10, D-07745 Jena, Germany; University of Hohenheim, Institute for Soil Science, Emil-Wolff Straße 27, D-70593 Stuttgart, Germany","Jungkunst, H.F., Max-Planck-Institute for Biogeochemistry, Hans-Knöll-Straße 10, D-07745 Jena, Germany; Fiedler, S., University of Hohenheim, Institute for Soil Science, Emil-Wolff Straße 27, D-70593 Stuttgart, Germany","The scientific Global Change debate is hampered by the insufficient knowledge of ""greenhouse gas"" fluxes. Thereby, extrapolations of global warming potentials of soil derived trace gas fluxes are sources of greatest uncertainties. At single ecosystems gas fluxes still show highly variable thus hardly predictable fluxes. Our main thesis was that geomorphology helps to explain much of the variability even at this detailed scale, i. c. under rather uniform ecological condition as seen from the surface. This thesis was tested at a site in Wildmooswald (Black Forest/SW- Germany) where recently soil individual fluxes were identified, but not the cause of the formation of such diverse and mainly hydromorphic pedosphere. The idea was that the periglacial slope deposits including a water-logging layer form a more complex relief than the present rather uniform relief. Thus explaining the diverging soil water and gas balances. The water-logging layer was mapped by a regular auger grid (25 × 20 m). The Global Warming Potential (CH4, N2O) was calculated by gas specific warming potential and area proportion of each soil type. Upper and lower relief were not congruent, thus the relief of periglacial slope deposits is explaining the spatial variability of N2O and CH4 emissions. The study field emitted 1,059 kg Of CO2 equivalents ha a-1 in average, whereas most estimates not considering the spatial distribution of the periglacial slope deposits would be around 355 kg not capable of explaining measured high spatial variability. © 2005 Gebrüder Borntraeger, D-14129 Berlin · D-70176 Stuttgart.",,"geomorphology; methane; nitrous oxide; soil emission; Antidesma platyphyllum",,,,,,"Anthoni, P.M., Knohl, A., Rebmann, C., Freibauer, A., Mund, M., Zielger, W., Kolle, O., Schulze, E.-D., Forest and agricultural land use dependent CO2 exchange in Thuringia, Germany (2004) Global Change Biol., 10, pp. 2005-2009; Corre, M.D., Pennock, D.J., van Kessel, C., Elliott, D.K., Estimation of annual nitrous oxide emissions from a transitional grassland-forest region in Saskatchewan, Canada (1999) Biogeochemistry, 44, pp. 29-49; Davidson, E.A., Fluxes of nitrous oxide and nitric oxide from terrestrial ecosystems (1991) Microbial Production and Consumption of Greenhouse Gases; Methane, Nitrogen Oxides and Halomethanes, pp. 219-235. , American Society of Microbiology; Systematik der Böden und der bodenbildendcn Substrate Deutschlands (1998) Mitt. Der Dt. Bodenkundl. Gesellsch., 86, pp. 1-180. , DBG; Einsele, G., Ricken, W., Eintiefungsgeschichte und Stoffhaushalt im Wutachgebiet (SW-Deutschland) (1993) Tübinger Geowissenschaftliche Arbeiten, 15, pp. 1-215. , (Hrsg.); Ellenberg, H., Mayer, R., Schauermann, J., (1986) Ökosystemforschung: Ergebnisse Des Sollingprojekts 1966-1986, pp. 1-507. , Ulmer Verlag, Stuttgart; (1998) World Reference Base of Soil Resources, , FAO Rome; Fiedler, S., Höll, B.S., Jungkust, H.F., Methane budget of a Black Forest spruce ecosystem considering soil pattern (2005) Biogeochemistry, , (in press); (2001) Climate Change 2001, , http://www.grida.no/climate, IPCC; Jungkust, H.F., Fiedler, S., Stahr, K., N2O emissions of a mature Norway spruce (Picea abies) stand in the Black Forest (southwest Germany) as differentiated by the soil pattern (2004